actions.comment:
The `SkiaSharp.Skottie` package already supports loading animations from an in-memory JSON string.

Use `Animation.Parse(string json)` (or `Animation.TryParse`) directly:

```csharp
using SkiaSharp.Skottie;

// jsonString is the Lottie JSON downloaded from your server
var animation = Animation.Parse(jsonString);
if (animation != null)
{
    // In your SKCanvas PaintSurface handler:
    animation.Seek(progress); // 0.0 to 1.0
    animation.Render(canvas, destRect);
}
```

Alternatively, if you prefer streams:

```csharp
using var stream = new System.IO.MemoryStream(System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(jsonString));
var animation = Animation.Create(stream);
```

Note: `SKLottieView` is not a built-in SkiaSharp control — use `Animation` from `SkiaSharp.Skottie` together with `SKCanvasView` to render animations. You can find a full example in the [SkiaSharp samples gallery](https://github.com/mono/SkiaSharp/blob/main/samples/Gallery/Shared/Samples/LottiePlayerSample.cs).
